04677nam a22006735i 9781478021681DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020048995  a97814780216817 a10.1515/97814780216812doi  a(DE-B1597)600472  a(OCoLC)1269268500  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aN66b.H64 2021 4aN66b.H64 2021 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.042231 aHoelscher, Jason A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt as Information Ecology :bArtworks, Artworlds, and Complex Systems Aesthetics /cJason A. Hoelscher. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThought in the Act : 1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Art is fuzzy information -- tChapter 1 Art and Differential objecthood -- tChapter 2 Aesthetic entropy machines -- tChapter 3 Butterfly effects in information space -- tChapter 4 Information efflorescence and the aesthetic singularity -- tChapter 5 Aesthetic amplification and adjacent possibility -- tChapter 6 Complex unities and complex boundaries -- tConclusion. Information entanglement and the post-evental artworld -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Art as Information Ecology, Jason A. Hoelscher offers not only an information theory of art but an aesthetic theory of information. Applying close readings of the information theories of Claude Shannon and Gilbert Simondon to 1960s American art, Hoelscher proposes that art is information in its aesthetic or indeterminate mode—information oriented less toward answers and resolvability than toward questions, irresolvability, and sustained difference. These irresolvable differences, Hoelscher demonstrates, fuel the richness of aesthetic experience by which viewers glean new information and insight from each encounter with an artwork. In this way, art constitutes information that remains in formation---a difference that makes a difference that keeps on differencing. Considering the works of Frank Stella, Robert Morris, Adrian Piper, the Drop City commune, Eva Hesse, and others, Hoelscher finds that art exists within an information ecology of complex feedback between artwork and artworld that is driven by the unfolding of difference. By charting how information in its aesthetic mode can exist beyond today's strictly quantifiable and monetizable forms, Hoelscher reconceives our understanding of how artworks work and how information operates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aArt, Americany20th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aInformation theory in aesthetics. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021681?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021681/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075403-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles